What are Hydroprocessing Catalysts (HPC)?

Hydroprocessing Catalysts (HPC) are specialized catalytic materials used in petroleum refineries to remove sulfur, nitrogen, metals, and other impurities from crude oil fractions through hydrogen-based refining processes. These catalysts play a critical role in hydrotreating and hydrocracking operations, enabling refineries to produce ultra-low sulfur diesel (ULSD), cleaner gasoline, jet fuel, and valuable petrochemical feedstocks while complying with increasingly stringent environmental regulations.

Modern hydroprocessing catalysts integrate advanced technologies including:

High-Activity Hydrotreating Catalysts for deep sulfur and nitrogen removal
Hydrocracking Catalysts for upgrading heavy crude fractions
Supported Metal Catalysts using nickel, cobalt, molybdenum, and tungsten
Advanced Alumina and Silica-Alumina Catalyst Supports
High Selectivity Catalyst Formulations for improved product yields
Long-Life Catalyst Technologies for extended operating cycles
By improving hydrogenation efficiency and impurity removal, hydroprocessing catalysts enable refineries to produce cleaner fuels, maximize refinery profitability, optimize heavy crude processing, reduce emissions, and comply with global fuel quality standards.

